<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900628-0015</DOCNO><DOCID>900628-0015.</DOCID><HL>   SEC Authority to Impose   Fines Clears House Panel</HL><DATE>06/28/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19</SO><IN>STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)</IN><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)SECURITIES AND EXCHANGE COMMISSION (SEC)</GV><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The House Energy and Commerce Committeeapproved by voice vote a bill that would give the Securitiesand Exchange Commission the power to impose fines for avariety of securities-law violations.   The SEC's authority to levy fines currently is limited toinsider-trading cases. For other violations, such asshort-selling offenses or fraudulent sales practices, theagency must choose between an injunction or barring theoffender from the securities industry altogether.</LP><TEXT>   In addition to giving the SEC the power to impose fines,the bill would allow the commission to imposecease-and-desist orders against securities-law violators.&quot;This injunctive remedy would mean the SEC would no longer berequired to go to court to secure a temporary restrainingorder or permanent injunction,&quot; said Rep. Matthew Rinaldo(R., N.J.).   The bill also would permit the SEC to ask courts toprohibit people convicted of a securities-law violation fromserving on the board of a public company. Moreover, the billwould let the SEC impose on violators fines of up to $100,000for individuals and $500,000 for firms, or the amount oftheir profits, whichever is greater. The bill is identical inmost respects to a measure passed by the Senate BankingCommittee.   The committee also passed by voice vote legislation aimedat curbing fraud and abuse in the penny-stock market. Thebill would, among other things, substantially increasedisclosure requirements for some penny-stock issues andexpand SEC power to bar crooked penny-stock salespeople fromthe securities industry.</TEXT></DOC>